Study Information 
Hypotheses 
H*:  Partner’s attention toward a target person would increase the target’s intimacy with the 
partner 
 
Expected pattern of results: Intimacy will increase as attention increases (based on Ohtsubo et 
al, 2014). 
 
“Attention” is operationalized as the camera turning on during the zoom where the RA will be 
seen observing the participant during a quiz task. 
 
“Intimacy” is operationalized as an index of four intimacy question items that were combined to 
create an intimacy scale. 
 
Design Plan 
Study type 
Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or 
lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized 
controlled trials. 
Blinding 

For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they 
have been assigned. 
Is there any additional blinding in this study? 
Participants will be blind to condition; it is not possible to blind RAs or the Experimenter to the 
condition (given the design of the study). 
Study design 
This is a between subjects design, where mean intimacy scores will be compared between two 
groups, the “attention” group and the “no attention” group. 
No files selected 
Randomization 
Participants will be randomized into either the “attention” or “no attention” groups. 
 
Randomization will be accomplished through block randomization accomplished through Excel. 
 
Note that participants will be told they are being randomized into being either “player 1” or 
“player 2”, but will always be player 2.  They will also be told they are being randomized to 
either “receive hints” or “cannot receive hints” but will always be without hints.  These are part 
of the cover story and not considered randomization. 
 
Sampling Plan 
Existing Data 
Registration prior to creation of data 
Explanation of existing data 
This project is being preregistered prior to any new data collection. 
Data collection procedures 
Participants will be recruited via a recruiting message sent to the university message center. 
This will result in all undergraduate and graduate students at RIT receiving an email detailing 
the basics of the study and how to sign up.  
 
At the start of the study, participants will be told: “You are about to participate in a paired study 
with another peer who is participating at the same time at their own residence. This study is 
focused on the problem solving people use in approaching a difficult quiz. You will receive five 
dollars for participating in this study along with a bonus of 10 cents for each problem you solve 
correctly in the quiz.   
 
You will be randomly assigned to a role – named either Player One or Player Two. Player One 
will be able to monitor the question that Player Two is currently working on. When Player One 

finds that Player Two happens to be working on the same question that he/she is working on, 
Player One is allowed to offer hints in some conditions. In other conditions, Player One is not 
allowed to offer hints. 
 
Do you have any questions? Okay, let me see what condition you have been assigned to (the 
experimenter checks his/her phone). You have been assigned the role of Player Two – where 
you may be monitored by your peer and you are NOT allowed to receive any hints.” 
 
Participants will then begin the computer program starting with the quiz. In the attention 
condition, the RA will leave the zoom camera on the entire time (the RA will maintain focus on 
the screen, but will not engage in idle conversation). In the no attention condition, the camera 
will be turned off. 
 
After finishing the quiz game, the participants will fill out the questionnaires containing four 
intimacy items: understanding (If you became friends with the partner, how well do you think 
this person would understand you?), validation (If you became friends with the partner, how 
much do you think this person would accept you?), caring (How much did the partner care for 
you?), and an additional reversed item corresponding to caring (How much do you agree that 
this partner had little concern for you?). These items are rated on a 7-point scale (1 = not at all 
to 7 =very much). The four items are aggregated as the intimacy score. The participants' interest 
in being friends with the partner was also assessed by two items: “How much are you 
interested in being friends with the partner?” and “How much do you agree that the partner 
and you will be good friends?” These items were aggregated as the interest in friendship score. 
 
Participants will also complete basic demographics (age, sex, race). 
 
Finally, the experimenter will complete a verbal suspicion probe and funneled debriefing. 
 
 
PLEASE SEE BELOW FOR EXACT MATERIALS 
 
This is an informed consent form for the research project titled “A conceptual replication of 
Ohtsubo et al. (2014)” being conducted by Dr. John Edlund a professor at the Rochester Institute 
of Technology. The purpose of this study is to investigate whether a particular study published 
in 2014 will replicate.  
  
Research participants will be asked to do the following: complete a 20 item trivia quiz, answer a 
series of questions about a partner, and answer a series of demographic questions.   
  

Research participation is voluntary, and may be withdrawn at any time without penalty or 
prejudice, and that if research participants have any additional questions concerning this study, 
they may contact Dr. Edlund at (585) 475-7475. If research participants want further 
information regarding their rights as a research subject, they may contact the Human Subjects 
Research Office at the Rochester Institute of Technology at (585) 475-2411. 
  
This project is sponsored by the Department of Defense through an award to the Center for 
Open Science. As a result, authorized representatives from a Department of Defense Human 
Research Protection Program may review and/or obtain information related to your 
participation in this research study as part of their responsibility to protect human research 
subject volunteers. 
  
This experiment will take approximately twenty minutes. Participants will receive five dollars for 
the study with a potential to win additional funds for answering the quiz items correctly (10 
cents for each correct answer). 
  
The intended benefits of this study include: demonstrating the replicability of scientific studies 
more generally along with a technique to predict which studies may be more (or less) likely to 
replicate.   
  
There are no reasonably foreseeable risks and/or discomforts research participants could 
experience during this study. All information gathered during this experiment will be kept 
confidential by having no names linked to the data gathered. De-identified/anonymous data will 
be shared on the Open Science Framework’s website. 
  
Consent to participate in this project does not constitute a waiver of any legal rights or redress 
the research participant might have as a result of my participation, and they acknowledge that 
they have received a copy of this consent form. 
  
